  "prompt": "What is the business plan of patanjali? Have they survive for profit or social work?",
  "response": "Patanjali, founded by Baba Ramdev and Acharya Balkrishna in 2006, has a unique business model that combines traditional Ayurvedic principles with modern marketing strategies. Here's an overview of their business plan and approach:\n\nBusiness Model:\n1. Product Range\n- FMCG products\n- Ayurvedic medicines\n- Food and beverages\n- Personal care items\n- Herbal and natural products\n\nCore Strategies:\n1. Swadeshi (Indigenous) positioning\n2. Low-cost, affordable products\n3. Natural and traditional ingredients\n4. Strong brand association with yoga and Baba Ramdev\n\nProfit and Social Work Approach:\n- Primary focus: Profitable business\n- Secondary objective: Social welfare and promoting Indian traditional knowledge\n- Aims to provide affordable, natural alternatives to market products\n- Emphasizes health and wellness\n\nKey Business Strengths:\n1. Strong distribution network\n2. Competitive pricing\n3. High brand recall\n4. Celebrity endorsement through Baba Ramdev\n5. Large consumer trust in natural products\n\nFinancial Performance:\n- Rapid growth since inception\n- Annual revenue around \u20b910,000 crore\n- Significant market share in FMCG segment\n\nWhile Patanjali has social welfare elements, its primary goal remains a profitable business model.",
